Sophora davidii (Franch.) Pavol.
( Fabaceae ; synonym
Sophora viciifolia Hance
) is a deciduous shrub, growing on hillside, wayside and sandy places in valleys in the Yunnan , Sichuan , Ningxia , and Guizhou provinces (
;
). The roots, leaves, flowers, and fruits of
S. davidii
have been used by local people as folk medicines. The roots have been used to treat cough, sore throat, dysentery, and hematochezia, etc (
). Many minorities in the Yunnan province of China , such as Yi, Bai, Miao, etc., have the tradition of using flowers as food. Conventionally, after being quickly dipped in boil water, then cleaned and soaked in water for 1–2 days, the flower of
S. davidii
is cooked with egg, chicken, or meat for the remedy of heat stroke, night sweat, oedema, etc (
).

As reported previously, the phytochemical research of 

S. davidii

have focused on the seeds and branches, and some flavonoids, alkaloids, and stilbene oligomers showed diversified bioactivities, including antiinflammatory, antitumor, and antiallergic activities (

; 

; 

). However, few studies on the chemical constituents of its flowers have been reported. We previously reported four new quinolizidine alkaloids from its flowers collected from Urumqi, 
Xinjiang Province
, 
China
(

). Since different ecological environments of plants may lead to the difference of specialised metabolites (

). We continued to explore structurally novel quinolizidine alkaloids of 

S. davidii

collected from Honghe county, 
Yunnan Province
, 
China
. As a result, three unusual matrine–adenine hybrids, named sophovicines A–C (1–3), as well as biogenetically related compound sophocarpine (4), were isolated and identified (
Fig. 1
).

Human cytomegalovirus (HCMV) is an opportunistic pathogen leading to life-threatening disease in immune-compromised patients and to significant congenital disease following primary infection of pregnant women (

). Currently, three licensed antiviral drugs are used for the prevention and/or treatment of HCMV infection: ganciclovir (VAL) (

), foscavir (FOS) (

), and cidofovir (CDV) (

). However, the prevalence of drug-resistant and cross-resistant strains of HCMV has severely reduced the effectiveness of these drugs (

; Lurain and Chou 2015; 

). Moreover, these drugs also effectuate obvious adverse reactions, such as bone marrow suppression, nephrotoxicity, neutropenia, thrombocytopenia, and electrolyte disturbance (

; 

; 

).

Nucleoside and nucleotide analogs are the focus of current interest as antiviral and antitumor agents. A great number of HCMV inhibitors are concentrated in this group of compounds (
Fig. 2
). The HCMV protease is essential for proper assembly of viral capsids and replication (

). So, a great deal of attention is being paid to it as therapeutic targets for the development of anti-HCMV drugs (

; 

). Based on the existence of adenine group in compounds 1–3, we speculate that 1–3 may have anti-HCMV activity. So, molecular docking studies were carried out between compounds 1–4 with HCMV protease. The results revealed that compounds 2 and 3 could be buried into the hydrophobic pocket of HCMV protease. Therefore, the inhibit effects of compounds 1–4 on HCMV were evaluated. The results show that compounds 2 and 3 can inhibit HCMV replication effectively with IC 
50
values of 7.12 and 7.32 
μ
M, respectively. Herein, the isolation, structural elucidation and biological evaluation of the isolated alkaloids are discussed.

Detailed analyses of the NMR data and molecular formula implied that 1 may be a dimer composing of matrine (1a) (
), and adenine (1 b) (
) moieties. The most remarkable difference was the methylene ( δ C 33.0) at C- 14 in matrine was replaced by a methine ( δ C 56.9) in 1, suggesting the matrine and adenine units may be connected by the bond between C-14 and N-9’. The C-14 ( δ C 56.9), C-4’ ( δ C 150.9), and C-8’ ( δ C 142.8) were connected by a nitrogen atom, which was demonstrated by the HMBC ( Fig. 3 ) correlations between H-14 and C-4 ′ and C-8 ′ , and between H-8 ′ and C-14. The matrine unit was further confirmed by the 1 H– 1 H COSY correlation peaks of H 2 -2/H 2 -3/H 2 -4/H-5/H-6/H-7/H 2 -8/H 2 -9/H 2 -10, H-5/H 2 -17, and H-7/H-11/H 2 -12/H 2 -13/H-14, together with HMBC correlations between H-2 and C-6 and C-10, H 2 -10 and C-6, H-11, and C-15, H-14 and C-15, and H 2 -17 and C-11 and C-15 ( Fig. 3 ). Apart from 1a structure, the remaining five carbon signals ( δ C 120.1, 142.8, 150.9, 153.5, and 157.1) assigned to 1 b (
). With these data, finally, the planar structure of 1 was determined.

Considering three new compounds contain adenine units, molecular docking studies between all isolates with HCMV protease (PDB: 2WPO) were carried out (

; 

). As illustrated in 
Fig. 7
, both compounds 2 and 3 could bind to the active pocket with stretched poses. In detail, 2 and 3 share a very similar binding mode, besides strong hydrogen bond (HB) interactions (2.46 and 2.10 Å) with the same residue GLY164 were detected in both modes, weak HB interaction with CYS161 (3.58 Å) and strong HB interaction with SER135 (2.09 Å) were found in 2 and 3, respectively (
Fig. 6B and C
). In addition, π- cation and π- π interactions between the adenine moieties of 2 and 3 with HIS63 were observed; meanwhile, one more π- cation interaction with ARG165 was formed in binding mode of 2. Whereas, less interactions were found in binding modes of compounds 1 and 4 (
Fig. 6A and D
) suggesting that 2 and 3 may be active in inhibition of HCMV and more potent than compounds 1 and 4.

Cells and viruses: The human colorectal carcinoma (HRT-18) cells (ATCC CCL-244) were cultured in Roswell Park Memorial Institute 1640 medium (RPMI 1640, Hyclone, 
USA
). The primary human foreskin fibroblasts (HFF) were cultured in minimal essential medium (MEM) medium (Hyclone, 
USA
). All cells were supplemented with 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS), penicillin and streptomycin (100 U/mL and 100 μg/ mL, respectively, Gibco, 
USA
), and HRT-18 cells were cultured with additional 10 mM HEPES (Gibco, 
USA
). The VR-1558 strain of HCoV-OC43 was propagated in HRT-18 cells, and the titer of viral stock was determined by 50% tissue culture infective dose (TCID 
50
) according to the cytopathic effect by use of Reed-Muench method (Xia et al., 2019). A BAC clone of HCMV Towne strain expressing a 
gfp
gene in the viral genome was propagated in HFF, and viral titers were titrated by plaque assay on monolayer of HFF as described previously (

).
